Indeed, and the whole mining thing was supposed to protect BitCoin from=
 such=20
manipulation.

Granted, it made it hard, but at some point, with enough money/value in=
volved,=20
economy of scale made it viable. And that's what bothers me, and that's=
 my=20
question:
Is it possible to design a protocol in a way that makes economy of scal=
e not=20
work?

The BitCoin example is particularily complex, as there's no good way to=
 tell,=20
on the protocol level, "all those nodes are part of a single cartel,=20=

controlled by a single entity". But maybe there is a way of basing this=
 on=20
behaviour? If nodes X, Y, Z behave in a very similar manner, lower thei=
r=20
weight in consensual decisions?

Apologies for being vague; I just feel there's something to it, but can=
't=20
really put my finger on it.

I see economies of scale driving a lot of not-so-great outcomes=20
(centralisation of e-mail providers; centralisation of ISPs and the gen=
eral=20
Internet infrastructure, introducing single points of failure in many p=
laces).=20
And that makes me wonder what can be done about it.

